\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1\i0\ul\ulc0\cf1 Exchange Rates, Prices, Money Supply}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 (Work on this more...)}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Guild-related prices are mostly set centrally, though this is subject to both good communications and a willingness to obey the center. Price of agricultural goods tends to fluctuate from season to season. Open-air markets often permit open bargaining, though it is more restricted in Helioptic areas where the authorities \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93suggest\u8221\'94 certain price ranges. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Money supply is directed by what are effectively central banks and mints in Borded and Besquahoek, with the Beavertoon \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Board of Accountable Governance for the Oversight of Fair Trade and the Security of Exchange\u8221\'94 acting as an important secondary (or even primary) credit market. They don\u8217\'92t issue currency, but they do collect it, along with other \u8220\'93rarities\u8221\'94, as they call them, and hold them as backing for their letters of credit and their \u8220\'93hard chits\u8221\'94.  Whether they actually have hoarded enough to fully pay out should there ever be a \u8220\'93run\u8221\'94 on chits is not known. }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 There is nothing like a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93stock exchange\u8221\'94. Investment in a shipping adventure would be handled directly with the concerned parties in the east.  A rough kind of \u8220\'93commodities\u8221\'94 market occurs in several southern and eastern locales when ships arrive in port, at fall harvest time and in mid-spring, when buyers arrive to bid for goods, grain, herbs, etc. The largest ones occur in Barbel, Brokilly, Wye, Morilly and Ingar.}
